I’d lean into what is genuinely distinctive about Wild Hawg rather than trying to sound like every other energy brand. If your product is veteran-founded, that’s part of your story—but the ad should still focus on the benefit to the customer, not just the founder.

Here’s a concept that feels native to short-form video and is easy to shoot with a phone.

⸻

Campaign: “Chew. Don’t Chug.”

Hook (0–3 sec)
Camera on someone fumbling with an energy drink before work.

Voiceover:
“Still carrying around another giant can?”

Cut. Tosses the can aside.

⸻

Middle (3–12 sec)
Pull out a pouch of Wild Hawg Energy Gummies.

Quick cuts:

* Walking into the gym
* Heading into the office
* Driving to work
* Hiking
* Early morning with kids

Voiceover:
“Wild Hawg Energy Gummies. Energy that fits in your pocket—not your cup holder.”

⸻

Close-up (12–20 sec)

Person pops a gummy.

Voiceover:
“No shaking cans. No spills. No excuses.”

⸻

Ending (20–25 sec)

Product shot.

Text on screen:

CHEW. DON’T CHUG.

Wild Hawg Energy Gummies

“Pocket-sized energy for wherever the day takes you.”

CTA:

“Join the first Wild Hawg drop.”

⸻

Why I like it

It doesn’t compete by saying:

* “More caffeine!”
* “Hardcore!”
* “Extreme!”

Instead it introduces a simple, memorable category distinction:

Drink energy vs. Chewable energy

People remember contrasts much better than feature lists.

⸻

Pantheon version (using your Hammer idea)

We “hammer” the category.

Old category:

Energy Drink

Break it into:

* Carry
* Consume
* Spill
* Refrigerate
* Size
* Convenience

Repair it as:

Pocket Energy

Now Wild Hawg isn’t trying to be a better drink.

It’s trying to become the product people think of when they want energy that goes anywhere.

If I were building the brand over the next six months, I’d create 100+ ads, but every one would reinforce the same central idea from a different angle. That’s how brands become memorable—not by having 100 different messages, but by expressing one core idea in many creative ways.